content.raw:
No worries.   If you do that, every DensityEntry will be copied when you return the vector.   I think the pointers are less of an issue if they're declared const (pointer values can't be changed).    The vector of references would be something like:

private: std::vector<const DensityEntry &> entries;
content.html:
No worries. If you do that, every DensityEntry will be copied when you return the vector. I think the pointers are less of an issue if they're declared const (pointer values can't be changed). The vector of references would be something like:

private: std::vector<const DensityEntry &> entries;

I guess there is no need to change it as long as it is well documented. A pattern I've seen is something as follows, but it would be different from the rest of the ConfigWidget API... Maybe we can just keep it like this for now, I have no strong feelings about this.

      /// \brief Get density value from a child widget.
      /// \param[in] _name Name of the child widget.
      /// \param[out] _value Density value.
      /// \return True if the value is got successfully.
      public: bool DensityWidgetValue(const std::string &_name,
          double &_value);

content.raw:
We have 4 quantities which are interdependent here: density, mass, MOI and volume (shape). As a future feature, it might be interesting to let the user choose which one they want to "lock". 

For example:

1. Set the density to Iron 

2. Change the shape from a box to a cylinder

3. Currently, the mass stays the same and the density becomes custom. Alternatively, I could have "locked" the density so the mass would have changed instead. Or locked both mass and density, so the new cylinder would be automatically scaled to have the proper volume.

@spaepcke , thoughts?
content.html:
We have 4 quantities which are interdependent here: density, mass, MOI and volume (shape). As a future feature, it might be interesting to let the user choose which one they want to "lock".

For example:

  1. Set the density to Iron

  2. Change the shape from a box to a cylinder

  3. Currently, the mass stays the same and the density becomes custom. Alternatively, I could have "locked" the density so the mass would have changed instead. Or locked both mass and density, so the new cylinder would be automatically scaled to have the proper volume.

@spaepcke , thoughts?
